• DOMAIN: Semiconductor manufacturing process¶

• CONTEXT: A complex modern semiconductor manufacturing process is normally under constant surveillance via the monitoring of signals/variables collected from sensors and or process measurement points. However, not all of these signals are equally valuable in a specific monitoring system. The measured signals contain a combination of useful information, irrelevant information as well as noise. Engineers typically have a much larger number of signals than are actually required. If we consider each type of signal as a feature, then feature selection may be applied to identify the most relevant signals. The Process Engineers may then use these signals to determine key factors contributing to yield excursions downstream in the process. This will enable an increase in process throughput, decreased time to learning and reduce the per unit production costs. These signals can be used as features to predict the yield type. And by analysing and trying out different combinations of features, essential signals that are impacting the yield type can be identified.¶

• DATA DESCRIPTION: sensor-data.csv : (1567, 592)¶

The data consists of 1567 datapoints each with 591 features.
The dataset presented in this case represents a selection of such features where each example represents a single 
production entity with associated measured features and the labels represent a simple pass/fail yield for in house 
line testing. Target column  1 corresponds to a pass and 1 corresponds to a fail and the data time stamp is 
for that specific test point.

• PROJECT OBJECTIVE: We will build a classifier to predict the Pass/Fail yield of a particular process entity and analyse whether all the features are required to build the model or not.¶

COLUMNS = DF.columns

NULL_COLS = pd.DataFrame(columns = ['COLUMN_NAME','NULL_VALUES_COUNT'])

COLUMN_NAME = []
NULL_PER = []

for i in COLUMNS:
    PER = (DF[i].isnull().sum()/1567)*100
    if PER > 20:
        COLUMN_NAME.append(i)
        NULL_PER.append(PER)
        DF = DF.drop(columns = i)
    elif PER > 0 and PER < 20:
        DF[i] = DF[i].fillna(DF[i].mean())
        
NULL_COLS = pd.DataFrame(list(zip(COLUMN_NAME,NULL_PER)),columns = ['COLUMN_NAME','NULL_PER'])

D. Check for multi-collinearity in the data and take necessary action.¶

* FROM THE ABOVE CORRELATION MATRIX WE CAN SEE THAT THERE IS PRESENSE OF MULTI COLLIENEARITY.

* IN SIMPLE TERMS, WE CAN SAY THAT PRESENCE OF ONE FEATURE IS ENOUGH TO DECUCT THAT OTHER FEATURE WILL ALSO BE
  PRESENT.

* SO IN THIS SCENARIO, OUT OF BOTH FEATURES WE CAN HAVE THAT FEATURE THAT IS MORE COLLINEAR WITH TARGET VARIABLE

* LET US DROP THOSE FEATURES THAT ARE HAVING CORRELATION THRESHOLD GREATER THAN 75% AND KEEP THE REMAINING
In [21]:
# WE ARE USING VARIANCE INFLATION FACTOR TO DEAL WITH COLLINEARITY
# ANY COLUMN HAVING A VIF VALUE GREATER THAN 5 REPRESENTS THEY ARE HIGHLY COLLINEAR
# WE WILL CALCULATE VIF VALUE FOR ALL THE COLUMNS FIRST
# BUT WE WILL NOT DROP ALL THE COLUMNS THAT HAVE VALUE HIGHER THAN 5
# WE WILL DROP COLUMNS THAT HAVE VERY HIGH VIF VALUE FIRST AND THEN CALCULATE VIF AGAIN AND DROP OTHER COLUMNS

def DEAL_WITH_COLLINEARITY(DF_NEW):
    
    MULTI_COLLINEAR = pd.DataFrame()
    MULTI_FEATURES = DF_NEW.drop(columns = ['Pass/Fail'])
    MULTI_COLLINEAR["COLUMN"] = MULTI_FEATURES.columns
    MULTI_COLLINEAR["VIF_VALUE"] = [variance_inflation_factor(MULTI_FEATURES.values, i)
                          for i in range(len(MULTI_FEATURES.columns))]
    return MULTI_COLLINEAR

E. Make all relevant modifications on the data using both functional/logical reasoning/assumptions.¶

* WE HAVE ALREADY MADE MODIFICATIONS ON THE DATA USING LASSO REGRESSION.

* WE HAVE DEALT WITH MULTI COLLINEARITY USING VARIANCE INFLATION FACTOR.

* AFTER THIS WE HAVE DROPPED THOSE COLUMNS THAT ARE NOT HAVING 0 COEFFICIENT VALUE AND HIGH COLLINEAITY

* LASSO REGRESSION:

    THE REASON I CHOOSE LASSO REGRESSION IS WE CAN HAVE THE CO-EFFICIENT VALUES FOR THE FEATURES

    THIS VALUE WHEN IT IS ZERO, MEANS THAT THEY HAVE VERY LEAST VARIATION ON THE DATA SET

    DROPPING THESE COLUMNS MIGHT BE BETTER WHEN DEALING WITH HUGE AMOUNT OF COLUMNS.

* VARIANACE INFLATION FACTOR:

    THE REASON I USED THIS METHOD IS TO DEAL WITH COLLINEARITY.

    WE ALSO HAVE A LIBRARY COLLINEARITY IN PYTHON TO DEAL WITH THIS AND TRADITIONAL METHOD OF CALCULATING
    CORRELATION MATRIX AND DEALING WITH THIS

    I USED THIS METHOD TO SAVE TIME AND SPEED UP THE DATA CLEANSING PROCESS.

    VIF VALUE GREATER THAN 5 MEANS THE FEATURES ARE HIGHLY CORRELATED.

    BUT INSTEAD OF DROPPING ALL THE COLUMNS THAT HAVE VIF VALUE MORE THAN 5, WE USED STEP BY STEP METHOD

    I HAVE NOT DROPPED ALL THE COLUMNS THAT ARE HAVING VIF VALUE MORE THAN 5 TO AVOID MISSING OF THE ANY
    VITAL INFORMATION IN THE MODEL BUILDING. ALSO SINCE OUR MODEL IS DEALING WITH SIGNAL PROCESSING,
    ITS BETTER TO KEEP ADEQUATE INFORMATION RATHER THAN DROPPING ALL THE COLUMNS.

* DROPPING THE TIME COLUMN:

    ANOTHER MODIFICATION I HAVE DONE ON THIS IS DROPPING THE TIME COLUMN.

    I ASSUMED THAT OUTPUT OF THE SIGNAL IS NOT DEPENDENT ON THE TIME BUT RATHER ON THE STRENGTH OF THE SIGNAL

    INCASE WE NEED TO HAVE THE TIME COLUMN IN THE MODEL BUILDING, WE CAN DIS-INTEGRATE THE COLUMN INTO
    YEAR, MONTH, DAY AND TIME AND CHECK THE OUTPUT OF THE SIGNALS ON A PARTICULAR TIME.

ABOVE ARE THE MODIFICATIONS THAT I MADE ON THE DATA SET BASED ON MY ASSUMPTIONS AND FUNCTIONAL KNOWLEDGE.

4. Data pre-processing:¶

A. Segregate predictors vs target attributes.¶

* PREDICTORS: THESE ARE THE VARIABLES THAT ARE REQUIRED TO PREDICT THE TARGET VARIABLE.
              WE NEED A MINIMUM OF 1 PREDICTOR TO PREDICT THE TARGET VARIABLE.

* TARGET ATTRIBUTES: THESE ARE THE VARIABLE THAT ARE PREDICTED BY USING PREDICTORS.

IN OUR DATA FRAME, AFTER REFINING, WE CAN SAY THAT PASS/FAIL IS THE TARGET VARIABLE AND ALL OTHERS ARE 
PREDICTORS.
In [33]:
# PREDICTORS = ALL THE FEATURES "X" EXCEPT TARGET ATTRIBUTE THAT HELPS IN PREDICTING THE TARGET VARIABLE
# TARGET = ATTRIBUTE "Y" THAT NEEDS TO BE PREDICTED BASED ON TARGET VARIABLE USING THE SUITABLE MACHINE LEARNING MODEL

X = DF_NEW.drop(columns = 'Pass/Fail')

Y = DF_NEW['Pass/Fail']

B. Check for target balancing and fix it if found imbalanced.¶

In [34]:
print('BELOW ARE THE COUNTS OF TARGET VARIABLE PASS/FAIL:\n',Y.value_counts())

BELOW ARE THE COUNTS OF TARGET VARIABLE PASS/FAIL:
 -1    1463
 1     104
Name: Pass/Fail, dtype: int64

* -1 REPRESENTS THAT THE SIGNAL IS PASS AND 1 REPRESENTS THE SIGNAL IS FAIL.

* FROM THE ABOVE OUTPUT, WE CAN SEE THAT MORE SIGNALS ARE TENDING TOWARDS PASS CLASS (-1).

* MORE THAN 93% OF THE TARGET VARIABLE IS -1 (PASS) AND LESS THAN 7% IS 1 (FAIL).

* THERE IS A HUGE IMBALANCE IN THE TARGET VARIABLE WHERE ONE CLASS OF OUTPUT IS DOMINATING OTHER.

* WHEN WE BUILD A MODEL USING THIS DATA AS IS, MODEL INCLINES MORE TOWARDS -1 AS IT HAS MORE RECORDS.

* WE NEED TO BALANCE THE DATA SO THAT MODEL CAN LEARN AND CLASSIFY THE RECORDS TO EACH CLASS PROPERLY.

* WE WILL BALANCE THE DATA USING SMOTE OR RANDOM SAMPLING METHOD.

* USING THE STANDARD SCALER METHOD, WE STANDARDIZED THE DATA BEFORE THE SPLITTING

* WE SPLITTED THE DATA INTO 80% TEST DATA AND 20% TRAIN DATA

* THEN WE AGAIN SPLIT THE DATA INTO 75% TEST DATA AND 25% TRAIN DATA

* AT THE END, FROM THE OVERALL DATA WE SPLIT IT INTO 60% TRAINING, 20% VALIDATION AND 20% TESTING DATA.

def MODEL(MODEL_TYPE,X_TRAIN, Y_TRAIN, X_VAL, Y_VAL):
    RESULTS = pd.DataFrame()
    for name, model in MODEL_TYPE:
        MODEL_EVAL = model
        MODEL_EVAL.fit(X_TRAIN, Y_TRAIN)
        Y_PRED = MODEL_EVAL.predict(X_VAL)
        ACCURACY = accuracy_score(Y_VAL, Y_PRED)
        PRECISION = precision_score(Y_VAL, Y_PRED)
        RECALL = recall_score(Y_VAL, Y_PRED)
        F1_SCORE = f1_score(Y_VAL, Y_PRED)
        RESULTS = RESULTS.append(pd.Series([name,ACCURACY,PRECISION,RECALL,F1_SCORE]),ignore_index=True)
    RESULTS.columns = ['MODEL_NAME','ACCURACY','PRECISION','RECALL','F1-SCORE']
    return RESULTS

def CV_BESTMODEL(MODEL_TYPES,X_TRAIN,Y_TRAIN):
    MODEL_RESULTS = []
    MODEL_NAME = []
    scoring = 'accuracy'
    for name, model in MODEL_TYPES:
        KFOLD = model_selection.KFold(n_splits=10, random_state=7,shuffle=True)
        CV_RESULTS = model_selection.cross_val_score(model,  X_TRAIN,Y_TRAIN, cv = KFOLD, scoring=scoring)
        MODEL_RESULTS.append(CV_RESULTS)
        MODEL_NAME.append(name)
        msg = "%s: %f (%f)" % (name, CV_RESULTS.mean(), CV_RESULTS.std())
        print(msg)
    
    fig = plt.figure(figsize = (20,10))
    fig.suptitle('ALGORITHM COMPARISON')
    ax = fig.add_subplot(111)
    plt.boxplot(MODEL_RESULTS)
    ax.set_xticklabels(MODEL_NAME)
    plt.show()

def KFCV_BESTMODEL(MODEL_TYPES,X_TRAIN,Y_TRAIN):

def RSKFCV_BESTMODEL(MODEL_TYPES,X_TRAIN,Y_TRAIN):

    MODEL_NAME = []
    scoring = 'accuracy'
    for name, model in MODEL_TYPES:

        RSKFCV_RESULTS = model_selection.cross_val_score(model,  X_TRAIN,Y_TRAIN, cv = RSKFOLD, scoring=scoring)

4. USE RANDOMIZED SEARCH CV TO FIND THE HYPERPARAMETERS.

    NOTE: RANDOMIZED SEARCH METHOD PROVIDES A COMBINATION OF PARAMETERS THAT HAS BEST PERFORMANCE USING MODEL
          THESE PARAMETERS COMBINATION CHANGES AT EVERY RUN OF THE ML MODEL.
In [41]:
def BEST_MODEL_PARAMS(MODELS,X_TRAIN,Y_TRAIN):
    BEST_SCORE = []
    MODELAME = []
    for name, model, params in MODELS:
        SEARCH_BEST = RandomizedSearchCV(model, n_iter=10, scoring='accuracy',
                                         param_distributions = params, n_jobs=-1, cv=3, random_state=1)
        TUNE_RESULTS = SEARCH_BEST.fit(X_TRAIN, Y_TRAIN)
        print(name)
        print('*******************************************************************************************')
        print('BEST SCORE: %s' % TUNE_RESULTS.best_score_)
        print('BEST PARAMETERS: %s' % TUNE_RESULTS.best_params_)
        print('\n\n')
        MODELAME.append(name)
        BEST_SCORE.append(TUNE_RESULTS.best_score_)
    return MODELAME, BEST_SCORE

def CONFUSION_MATRIX(MODEL_TYPE):
    for name, model in MODEL_TYPE:
        MODEL_EVAL = model
        Y_PRED = MODEL_EVAL.predict(X_TEST)

        CM = metrics.confusion_matrix(Y_TEST, Y_PRED,labels=[-1, 1])

        CM_DF = pd.DataFrame(CM, index = [i for i in ["-1","1"]],
                  columns = [i for i in ["-1","1"]])

        plt.figure(figsize = (7,5))
        
        plt.title(name)

        sns.heatmap(CM_DF, annot=True ,fmt='g')
    
        plt.show()

def CLASSIFICATION_REPORT(MODEL_TYPE):
    RESULTS = pd.DataFrame()
    for name, model in MODEL_TYPE:
        MODEL_EVAL = model
        MODEL_EVAL.fit(X_TRAIN, Y_TRAIN)
        Y_PRED = MODEL_EVAL.predict(X_TEST)
        print('CLASSIFICATION REPORT FOR ',name)
        print('******************************************************************')
        print(classification_report(Y_TEST,Y_PRED),'\n')
